body:
This is a proof of concept PR, showing how to build pytorch with ROCm. 

@smuzaffar let me know if I should just run `pip install <wheel file>` as install step, instead of splitting a package into two.

One thing to note is that `aotriton` (or, to be exact, it's dependency `triton`) downloads it's dependencies - a custom LLVM and some CUDA tools (nvcc, for example). This can be disabled, but then we will need to provide these ourselves - which means keeping track of LLVM updates (triton needs a very specific commit of LLVM).
